300 501 1657 (A simple change can solve the first serious problem with injection.  Simply inject names when the) 1657 SB
300 551 1661 (template is defined.  Friend classes and friend class templates can be injected when the template is) 1661 SB
300 601 1781 (defined, because they can\222t depend on template parameters of the enclosing template.  Functions can, and) 1781 SB
300 651 1619 (usually do, depend on the template parameters of the enclosing templates, so the actual function) 1619 SB
300 701 1694 (signatures cannot be injected until the enclosing class instantiations are done.  However, a \223generic\224) 1694 SB
300 751 1742 (function or function template can be injected. When instantiations of the enclosing class take place, the) 1742 SB
300 801 1743 (real functions and function templates would be added to the overload set containing the \223generic\224 entry) 1743 SB
300 851 850 (created when the template definition was scanned.) 850 SB
300 951 1772 (I believe that this change would be sufficient, and would solve the problems as effectively as the proposal) 1772 SB
300 1001 1586 (by Bill Gibbons.  His proposal implicitly requires that the types of function arguments be fully) 1586 SB
300 1051 1780 (instantiated, if they had not been previously.  If such rules are used in conjunction with injection it makes) 1780 SB
300 1101 1522 (injection and Bill\222s alternative equivalent in terms of the second problem described above.) 1522 SB
300 1201 1771 (If this is not considered to be sufficient, a \223reconsideration\224 rule could be added.  Such a rule would state) 1771 SB
300 1251 1793 (that the result of any lookup that produced an overload set containing one of the \223generic\224 functions, must) 1793 SB
300 1301 1153 (produce the same result if repeated at the end of the translation unit.) 1153 SB
